"1364","avril 1387":"April 1387","1418":"1418","Longueval, 80490, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","France":"France","Brias, 62180, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Brias, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marguerite Marie DE LONGUEVAL was born in 1338, in Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France, her father, Chevalier Jean de Longueval, was 17 and her mother, Marguerite de Mortagne, was 35. She married Jean II DE FOSSEUX in 1354. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in April 1387, in Brias, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1338–avril 1387":"1338–aprill 1387","1338–1387":"1338–1387","1332–1364":"1332–1364","1332–Male":"1332–Surnud","1340–1418":"1340–1418","1355–1418":"1355–1418","1321–1350":"1321–1350","1303–1348":"1303–1348","3 septembre 1364":"3. september 1364","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1338":"1338","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1348":"1348","1303":"1303","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1321":"1321","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","avril 1387":"aprill 1387","1418":"1418","Longueval, 80490, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Brias, 62180, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Brias, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1338–avril 1387":"1338–huhtikuu 1387","1338–1387":"1338–1387","1332–1364":"1332–1364","1332–Male":"1332–Kuollut","1340–1418":"1340–1418","1355–1418":"1355–1418","1321–1350":"1321–1350","1303–1348":"1303–1348","3 septembre 1364":"3. syyskuuta 1364","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1338":"1338","Abt 1340":"noin 1340","1348":"1348","1303":"1303","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1321":"1321","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","avril 1387":"huhtikuu 1387","1418":"1418","Longueval, 80490, Somme, Picardi